Title: Iterative algorithms for two-dimensional helioseismic inversion  
Author: Rasmus Munk Larsen, 
Address: Aarhus, Ny Munkegade, building 540, DK-8000 Aarhus C, Denmark.  
Affiliation: Department of Computer Science, University of  
Abstract: In two-dimensional helioseismic inversion the observed frequencies of the Suns normal modes are used to make inferences about the solar rotation rate as a function of radius and latitude. The inversion methods currently used are either Subtractive Optimally Localized Averages (SOLA) and Regularized Least Squares (RLS), where the main computational burden lies in solving a regularized linear least-squares problem. Standard algorithms are usually based on some orthogonal matrix-factorization, e.g. a singular value decomposition (SVD), but for the two-dimensional helioseismic inversion, where the dimensions of the coeOEcient matrix in the discretized problem are potentially 10 6 fi 10 4 , this approach is prohibitively expensive. To develop more eOEcient algorithms we have to incorporate some special knowledge about the underlying physical problem. In this paper we show how insight into the properties of the continuous problem can be used to dramatically reduce the computational complexity and the amount of storage needed. It is shown that the coeOEcient matrix has a block Kronecker product structure, and we describe two iterative algorithms based on this observation that implement the SOLA inversion method. For large-scale helioseismic datasets the Kronecker product formulation typically reduces the computing time by two orders of magnitude. Finally we discuss the results and performance obtained with the new algorithms on data from the LOWL, GONG and MDI projects and compare it to that obtained using the algorithm described by Larsen and Hansen (1997). 
